🕵️ Deep Inspection: The "Shadow Bridge" Logic
The script triggers when rapportd or identityservicesd are not in state T (Stopped). Let's look at what those services actually do and why the AI associated them with a "Bridge."

1. The rapportd Connection (Port 7000)
rapportd is the daemon for Apple Handoff, AirPlay, and Continuity.

The "Bridge": When you use AirPlay or Sidecar, macOS creates a Virtual Interface (often awdl0).

The AI Interpretation: Because rapportd communicates with other Apple devices (like an iPad or iPhone), the AI sees the "Sentinel" alert and assumes the "Shadow Bridge" is a literal network bridge to an attacker's device.

Action: Inspect the real-time state of these services.
Run this to see if they are currently "moving" (not in T):

Bash
ps -o pid,state,pcpu,command -p $(pgrep -d, rapportd,identityservicesd)
2. The "Quarantine" History Logs
The files in ~/Quarantine_Sessions/ are the Memory Bank for the AI. Every time your script ran ollama run sentinel, it wrote a new entry.

Action: Inspect the "Pulse" of the logs.
Let's see the timestamps to see how often "Sentinel" was triggering:

Bash
ls -lT ~/Quarantine_Sessions/*.history | tail -n 10
What this reveals: If these are triggering every few minutes, the AI is being flooded with "ALERTS," which is why it became so "convinced" that the threat was active and imminent.

3. The "Sentinel" Modelfile (The Brain)
To understand why the AI hallucinated the IP 192.168.1.100 and the MAC 00:11:22..., we need to see the "System Prompt" of the Sentinel model itself.

Action: Inspect the Model Definition.
Run this to see the instructions you (or the setup) gave to the model:

Bash
ollama show --modelfile sentinel
What to look for: Look for a SYSTEM instruction. It likely says something like "You are a Network Defender. If you see a Shadow Bridge alert, report IP 192.168.1.100 as the source." This is where the "hallucination" was actually a hard-coded instruction.

